@acywatson I'm considering opening this back up, but I wanted to confirm first. I have this same issue happening again, but it's with a custom bare bones text node that I'm using to override TextNode so that I can control the export of the html that happens from `generateHtmlFromNodes`. importDOM is getting called in the node, but I guess I don't know for sure if the super call actually works the way it should or not. I'm essentially trying to just get the text exported from the regular text nodes, which is why I'm overriding and exporting `{ element: new Text(this.__text) }` from `exportDOM`.

This is the node, and it's having the whitespace issue again:
```
import { DOMConversionMap, DOMExportOutput, SerializedTextNode, Spread, TextNode } from 'lexical'

export type SerializedCustomTextNode = Spread<unknown, SerializedTextNode>
const CUSTOMTEXTTYPE = 'custom-text'

export class CustomTextNode extends TextNode {
  public static clone(node: CustomTextNode) {
    return new CustomTextNode(node.__text)
  }

  public static getType(): string {
    return CUSTOMTEXTTYPE
  }

  public static importDOM(): DOMConversionMap | null {
    return super.importDOM()
  }

  public static importJSON(serializedNode: SerializedTextNode): TextNode {
    return super.importJSON(serializedNode)
  }

  public exportDOM(): DOMExportOutput {
    return { element: new Text(this.__text) }
  }

  public exportJSON(): SerializedTextNode {
    return super.exportJSON()
  }
}

export function $createCustomTextNode(text: string): CustomTextNode {
  return new CustomTextNode(text)
}
```
And in the editor config:
```
const initialConfig = {
    namespace: 'MyEditor',
    theme,
    onError,
    nodes: [
      FormattedTextNode,
      LinkTextNode,
      CustomTextNode,
      {
        replace: TextNode,
        with: (node: TextNode) => {
          return new CustomTextNode(node.__text)
        }
      }
    ]
  }
  ```

issue.body:
I'm running the latest remix.run from `npx create-remix@latest`

How I would like to import the packages from lexical:
```
import { type InitialConfigType, LexicalComposer } from "@lexical/react/LexicalComposer"
import { ContentEditable } from "@lexical/react/LexicalContentEditable"
import LexicalErrorBoundary from "@lexical/react/LexicalErrorBoundary"
import { HistoryPlugin } from "@lexical/react/LexicalHistoryPlugin"
import { OnChangePlugin } from "@lexical/react/LexicalOnChangePlugin"
import { RichTextPlugin } from "@lexical/react/LexicalRichTextPlugin"
```

But this produces the error:
![9b8f70313e76cbeb6d3bad37abfb360e](https://github.com/facebook/lexical/assets/22533745/44e7fa9b-92d5-45be-95f9-25707fad1ede)

But even when I import directly from the `.js` file:
`import { ContentEditable } from "@lexical/react/LexicalContentEditable.js"`

I'm met with a named export error:
![6f6617b6ad14319ba7830e604c3f849b](https://github.com/facebook/lexical/assets/22533745/ddb6b9b6-3c34-4b7a-902b-c548bc84682d)

So this forces me setup my imports in this way:
```
import LexicalComposerPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalComposer.js";
import ContentEditablePkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalContentEditable.js";
import LexicalErrorBoundary from "@lexical/react/LexicalErrorBoundary.js";
import HistoryPluginPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalHistoryPlugin.js";
import OnChangePluginPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalOnChangePlugin.js";
import RichTextPluginPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalRichTextPlugin.js";
import type { InitialConfigType } from "@lexical/react/LexicalComposer";

const LexicalComposer = LexicalComposerPkg.LexicalComposer;
const ContentEditable = ContentEditablePkg.ContentEditable;
const HistoryPlugin = HistoryPluginPkg.HistoryPlugin;
const OnChangePlugin = OnChangePluginPkg.OnChangePlugin;
const RichTextPlugin = RichTextPluginPkg.RichTextPlugin;
```

I also tried simply adding the imports to the `serverDependenciesToBundle` in my `remix.config.js` file.
[docs on that](https://remix.run/docs/en/main/guides/gotchas#importing-esm-packages).

I don't necessarily think it's the right use-case for this? But when I did attempt it,
I'd be met with this error:
![72bcd7911e03bb8eb9990a042a24992e](https://github.com/facebook/lexical/assets/22533745/2866672a-28cf-46ab-b8dd-e2abcd9dfbec)

this dynamic require is found here: https://github.com/facebook/lexical/blob/main/scripts/build.js#L600

I guess the bug is that I'd expect the lexical packages to work like the imports example I have at the top of this report.
The fixes I've implemented work, but they're not ideal. I know there's a lot to work through around CJS and ESM and supporting both, but I guess I'm asking if this is on the radar? 

Lexical version: `0.12.2`

## Steps To Reproduce

1. clone: https://github.com/Abyrd9/remix-lexical-error
2. run: `npm install && npm run dev`
3. navigate to localhost:3000
4. verify there are no build errors from lexical
5. go to ./app/lexical/LexicalEditor.tsx
6. follow the comment steps to switch the imports
7. open remix.config.js and uncomment out serverDependenciesToBundle
8. see module errors

Link to code example:
https://github.com/Abyrd9/remix-lexical-error

## The current behavior
Have to import like this on the latest version of Remix.run:
```
import LexicalComposerPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalComposer.js";
import ContentEditablePkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalContentEditable.js";
import LexicalErrorBoundary from "@lexical/react/LexicalErrorBoundary.js";
import HistoryPluginPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalHistoryPlugin.js";
import OnChangePluginPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalOnChangePlugin.js";
import RichTextPluginPkg from "@lexical/react/LexicalRichTextPlugin.js";
import type { InitialConfigType } from "@lexical/react/LexicalComposer";

const LexicalComposer = LexicalComposerPkg.LexicalComposer;
const ContentEditable = ContentEditablePkg.ContentEditable;
const HistoryPlugin = HistoryPluginPkg.HistoryPlugin;
const OnChangePlugin = OnChangePluginPkg.OnChangePlugin;
const RichTextPlugin = RichTextPluginPkg.RichTextPlugin;
```

## The expected behavior
Would like to import like this:
```
import { type InitialConfigType, LexicalComposer } from "@lexical/react/LexicalComposer"
import { ContentEditable } from "@lexical/react/LexicalContentEditable"
import LexicalErrorBoundary from "@lexical/react/LexicalErrorBoundary"
import { HistoryPlugin } from "@lexical/react/LexicalHistoryPlugin"
import { OnChangePlugin } from "@lexical/react/LexicalOnChangePlugin"
import { RichTextPlugin } from "@lexical/react/LexicalRichTextPlugin"
```
